Method 2

The probability, $p$, that the lamp is on
= \text{the probability that } S_1 \text{ and } S_2 \text{ are on or } S_3 \text{ and } S_4 \text{ are on}
= \text{the probability that } S_1 \text{ and } S_2 \text{ are on}
+ \text{the probability that } S_3 \text{ and } S_4 \text{ are on}
- \text{the probability that } S_1 \text{ and } S_2 \text{ and } S_3 \text{ and } S_4 \text{ are on}
$$= \left(\frac{1}{3} \times \frac{1}{3}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{3} \times \frac{1}{3}\right) - \left(\frac{1}{3} \times \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{1}{3}\right) = \frac{1}{9} + \frac{1}{9} - \frac{1}{81} = \frac{17}{81}.$$ 
Hence $729p = 17 \times 9 = 153$.

Method 3

The probability, $p$, that the lamp is on
= 1 - \text{the probability the lamp is off}
= 1 - \text{the probability } S_1 \text{ or } S_2 \text{ is off and } S_3 \text{ or } S_4 \text{ is off}
= 1 - (\text{the probability } S_1 \text{ or } S_2 \text{ is off})^2
= 1 - (1 - \text{the probability } S_1 \text{ and } S_2 \text{ are on})^2
= 1 - \left(1 - \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2\right)^2 = 1 - \left(1 - \frac{1}{9}\right)^2 = 1 - \left(\frac{8}{9}\right)^2 = 1 - \frac{64}{81} = \frac{17}{81}$.
Hence $729p = 17 \times 9 = 153$.

