2011.statement_latex:
We try starting with some other small integers. The sequences in Part \textbf{a} contain all integers from 1 to 8 and the integers 10, 12, 13, 14. The snowstorms generated by 9, 11, 15, 16 start as follows:

$$
\begin{array}{l}
9 \rightarrow 26 \rightarrow 13 \\
15 \rightarrow 44 \rightarrow 22 \rightarrow 11
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{l}
11 \rightarrow 32 \rightarrow 16 \rightarrow 8 \\
16 \rightarrow 8
\end{array}
$$

So starting with an integer from 1 to 16 will lead to a cycle of length two or five. However 17 gives a cycle of length 18:

$$
\begin{array}{c|c}
17 & 50 \rightarrow 25 \rightarrow 74 \rightarrow 37 \rightarrow 110 \rightarrow 55 \rightarrow 164 \rightarrow 82 \\
\uparrow & \\
34 & 68 \rightarrow 136 \rightarrow 272 \rightarrow 91 \rightarrow 182 \rightarrow 61 \rightarrow 122 \rightarrow 41
\end{array}
$$

\textbf{c} \textbf{Alternative i}

If a number is multiplied by three and then 1 is subtracted, the result cannot be a multiple of three. So, if a cycle contains a multiple of three then it must have been obtained by halving its predecessor. Hence that predecessor is also a multiple of three. By the same argument, it was obtained by halving the next predecessor, and so on. Thus, going backwards through the cycle, the snowflakes double. Hence we will never get back to the original multiple of three. So there is no multiple of three in a cycle.

\textbf{Alternative ii}

Any even snowflake is divided by two so will eventually lead to an odd snowflake. So a cycle of snowflakes must contain an odd number, $t$ say. The next snowflake is $3t - 1$ which is even. So we divide by two until we get another odd number $u$ say. None of these snowflakes after $3t - 1$ can be a multiple of three because this would mean that $3t - 1$ is a multiple of three. The snowflake after $u$ is $3u - 1$ which is even. Thus continuing the cycle of snowflakes produces no multiple of three.

\textbf{Alternative iii}

Any cycle that contains a multiple of three will contain an odd multiple of three because any even snowflake is divided by two until an odd snowflake is produced.

The next snowflake after an odd multiple of three is not a multiple of three. If $n$ is not a multiple of three and is even, then the next snowflake is $\frac{n}{2}$ which is not a multiple of three. If $n$ is not a multiple of three and is odd, then the next snowflake is $3n - 1$ which is not a multiple of three. Thus all snowflakes after an odd multiple of three are not multiples of three. Hence no cycle contains an odd multiple of three.

So no cycle contains a multiple of three.
